This lawyer Ignoramus of Ruggle's drama is introduced, sc. I, 3, in the role of the “ pedant in love '' (for history of this character see Oreizenach's Geschichte des neueren DramaS, Bd. II, s. 280). Mr. Ruggle seems to have been influenced in this respect especially by the Latin drama “ Pedantius ’' enacted also in the presence of Cambridge scholarS, according to Prof. Smith as early as 1581. (See edit. of Ped., p. x.) ⁴ One of the differentiating features of Pedantius from other dramas of its genus is the manner in which its hero uses in his con- versations with his three pupils, in his wooing of Lydia, on all occasions a multitude of academical saws and philosophical phrases, In exactly the ‘same peculiar manner Ignoramus in· serts into his intercourse with his three clerks as well as into his passionate love-suit of Rosabella a mass of legal terms and phrases.
